I want to work in social work. I want to help children who have been hurt or ignored. I also want to support difficult families. Important values I bring to this work are service, respect, and wanting to help others. These values are important to me and to the work of social workers.

I have always wanted to help others, but I was not sure what job to do. In high school and college, I saw people avoid their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. Because of this, I studied Psychology. I still did not know what job to do after college. So, I took a break. One day, I visited a friend. She had a sixteen-year-old boy with her. He was scared to be at her house because his parents were hurting him. I went to his house to help. I talked to the police about what was happening. The police asked me to talk to his parents. I did, but they did not seem to care. They blamed their son for the problems. After this, I thought about being a social worker to help children with family problems.

Social justice is also important. Society says each person is important, but it wants everyone to be the same. I believe in being myself. In high school and college, I protested social injustice. I colored my hair differently, wore clothes I liked, pierced my ears, and fought against racism and discrimination. I will always believe in social justice.

The paper is about the Biological and Sociocultural models of insomnia. The Biological model looks at genes and health. The Sociocultural model looks at the environment and things related to race, ethnicity, and money. The paper explains each model and how research relates to them. The explanations and results are critiqued.

Sleep disorders have three types: those with no other cause, those with a cause, or those with a mental or other health problem. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Dyssomnias have trouble with sleep. Parasomnias have sleep problems with behaviors or physical things. Related sleep problems have causes from mental or other health issues. The paper focuses on insomnia and primary sleep disorders.

The Biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes and physiology. The hypothalamus has orexin neurons that regulate sleep and wakefulness. A study with mice found GABAB receptors on these neurons. The GABAB receptor promotes sleep. If it is blocked, sleep is reduced. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time. This means that sleep problems can be caused by genes and the environment. If the receptor is not working right, sleep may be bad. This can affect school, work, and daily tasks.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). The first part explains what CAPD is. The next part talks about how to know if someone has CAPD. Finally, the paper talks about ways teachers can help students with CAPD in regular classrooms.

CAPD is a problem with how the brain uses and understands things that we hear. People with CAPD can hear normally, but their brains do not process sounds as they should. This means they may have trouble with sounds, like understanding what someone is saying or hearing sounds in space.

The first mention of CAPD was in the 1950s, called "auditory imperception". In 1977, a conference helped start research on CAPD. People with CAPD may have trouble hearing sounds in space, understanding different sounds, hearing sound patterns, or understanding changes in speech. They may also have trouble with sounds blocking other sounds or understanding the sequence of sounds.

To find out if someone has CAPD, they need to take tests. These tests look at how well the person listens and responds to sounds. No one tool is always used to find CAPD. There are many tests, like listening to words or numbers and recording sounds in the ear. There is no known cause for CAPD.

Teachers can help students with CAPD by:
- Providing clear instructions
- Talking clearly and slowly
- Testing in a quiet place
- Using visual aids
- Checking for understanding

The play Twelfth Night shows that disguise can be useful for deception, but it is important to drop the disguise so one does not lose their true self. Ending deception can cause people to feel alone. One must choose between protecting themselves or preserving relationships. Some people may not mind being tricked, but others will be upset.

The topic of men pretending to be women, or vice versa, is difficult because it brings up many other problems. The main question is: why does someone feel they need to pretend? Viola pretends to be a man to protect herself in a new land. Her plan works, but she feels alone. She also causes confusion with Olivia, who loves her as if she is a man. Viola has feelings for Orsino, who says she should not love a woman like her.

Twelfth Night shows how deception can help people discover hidden feelings. Olivia and Orsino may have secret desires that Viola's disguise forces them to deal with. For example, Olivia might love women, not just men.

Olivia easily shifts her love from Cesario to Sebastian. She sees Cesario/Viola as a sister, not a love interest. This shows Olivia judges people based on their looks.

German colonial rule was known for its cruelty, especially in the case of the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. No single description can cover all of German colonial rule. The empire was very different in its policies and ruling style across different colonies. Education in these colonies was also varied. When the British took German East Africa, they found many educated Africans. In Kamerun and other colonies, German education was praised. However, the situation in South West Africa was different. Unlike in East Africa, the German government did not teach many native people. Instead, they left education mostly to missionaries. The government did support European education and created schools for them. These policies had long effects on South West Africa. Many people in the colony were not educated. Many reasons caused this difference. This paper will discuss these reasons and new research on settlers' and colonial authorities' views on native Africans. There are many books about education in the German colonial empire. Most are in German and were written after the colonial period. Early books described educational systems. Later books in English compared and studied education in different colonies. The most important book that talks about this topic is Cohen's study of South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compared these colonies' educational systems and found that the large settler population in South West Africa made their educational system different. South West Africa's climate was temperate, but it had a large desert area. The European population was about 15,000 people in 1913, while East Africa had only 5,336.

Music grows in popular song since 100 years. Now, many styles of music exist. Each has many sub-styles, too. Heavy Metal is one of the most popular styles. It has many sub-styles, too. It started 40 years ago and grew with different styles. Now, it is a big movement with many styles. People call it "music of more." It has a lot of bass and volume. It is full of emotions, but often dark. The music is very good. People in bands know how to play their instruments. The music has many qualities, like drugs. Many people use drugs to make music. This is not new. It is based on old songs. The Beatles sang dark songs, too. Their song "Helter Skelter" is like the first heavy metal song. It was a answer to the Rolling Stones. The Beatles wanted to be as heavy as the Rolling Stones.

Henri Rousseau, a Post-Impressionist artist, painted many dream-like pictures. One famous one is called "The Dream." This painting shows a woman in a dream. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and goals as a painter. As a painter, Rousseau wanted to be accepted by other artists and art lovers. He had two choices: follow the styles of other artists or be unique. He chose to be unique. This shows his internal struggle between these two choices.

Rousseau had a hard life. He grew up in a small town. His father was a tinsmith. He had no art training. He worked as a toll service employee until age 40. Then he started painting. He lost his wife and many children. He hoped painting would give him new life.

Rousseau wanted to be accepted by the art world. This was hard because he wasn't educated in painting and started late. But he didn't give up. He kept painting his own style. He wanted his paintings to be so good that people would accept him. This is his life's struggle.

Many people think there is a close link between ethics and beauty. I agree. John Keats wrote that "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn about good and beauty in many ways, but we often enjoy them without learning. Both are about describing, not telling what to do. We try to explain why something is good art or moral, not just judge it. Art criticism can't capture the full meaning of good art. People say, "There's just something about it" when they like a work. Both art and ethics are more than just description. They have something extra, something that can't be explained. Like Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." Ethics is like this too. Ethics is like art in many ways. They both touch us deeply in a way that can't be fully explained. Literature has this moral quality. It's like life itself, McKean said. Living involves values, and literature is important because of them.

Germany is strong and united. It has a unique culture from the Alps in München to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This culture is also found in Köln on the Rhine River and in Dresden on the Elbe River. This unique culture comes from many different sources and tribes.

Germany is the home of the Germans. The name "Germany" comes from a Germanic tribe called Tungrians. The Romans used this name to distinguish between tribes they had conquered and those they had not. The name may also come from a spear called a "ger" or from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout." Some scholars believe the name means "loud" or "noisy."

The Roman historian Tacitus wrote about the Germans in his book "De Origine et situ Germanorum." He said the Germans were aboriginal and not mixed with other races. He also wrote that many people would not leave Rome to live in Germany because it had a difficult climate and people with a bad attitude.

The Romans did not live in Germany. They sent soldiers to fight in Germania and traded goods with the Germanic tribes. The Romans did not stay in Germania. They returned to their empire. The Germanic tribes lived near the Roman Empire and traded with them.

I looked down. My mind was empty. I saw the picture in front of me but did not understand it. I was calm. My hand moved on its own. I wanted to draw since I was six. I bought a book. It taught me how to draw. One technique was to place a frame around a picture. My mind could not do this. I was too amazed. I saw a bowl of fruit. It was like a Picasso, Monet, or Renaissance painting. My fingers touched the pencil. My hand moved. Water was clear and clean. The brown thing in the toilet would not move. I cleaned the toilet. My hand moved again.

Teenagers die in car accidents. Many things cause this problem. The brain of a teenager is not ready for driving. They are not experienced. This causes too many fatal accidents and other bad things like speeding and driving off the road.

Teenagers do worse when they drive with their friends. A study shows that the number of accidents goes up as the age of the friends goes up.

States try to make driving safer by giving teens limits on when and with whom they can drive. But these limits are not enough. Teenagers are not ready for driving. Even 18 is too young, says psychologist Marvin Zuckerman. He says teenagers like to take risks.

More teens will start driving in the next few years. We must do something. We could make a law. Schools could teach driving, but no one under 18 could drive. A permit could be given, but they would still need practice hours.

This law is not new. It could help all states and keep teens safe.

I looked at many old Edison trick films. There were 15 films from 1895 to 1901. These films use tricks in editing to make illusions. I studied these films to describe how they work. Most trick films use a fixed camera in a proscenium. The camera does not move. The actors usually only move side-to-side. They do not walk towards or away from the camera. For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors move right and left, but the camera does not follow. The camera is in one place, and actors move in front of it.

Most trick films have long or medium shots. They do not use close-ups. This is like theatre and vaudeville, where the whole performance is seen at once. Actors do not move towards the camera. Most trick films have one shot per film. This makes most films short, about one minute or less. They show short tricks, not long stories. One trick film shot may be several shots joined together. Look at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895). A close look shows the head shot is separate, but it looks like one shot.

John Taylor from Caroline was early and strong supporter of Republicanism. He was mainly farmer, but also had short career in politics. This made him known for his strong beliefs in personal freedom and government. His love for farming made him think about government a lot. He believed that the United States could create good system because there were no old traditions to stop them. He thought people have natural rights, and if one is taken away, others become less valuable. These rights should not be controlled by government. He said the best society is one where people have jobs that help each other, not just themselves.

Taylor thought government should have good and bad sides. He believed people have both good and bad in them. He said government must help people keep their private things, improve farming, and not let people take advantage of each other. He thought a government with good rules will work well, no matter who is in charge. He said people have self-interest, but it becomes bad when it hurts others. A good government is needed to keep people's bad sides under control.

Taylor, like other Republicans, wanted strict rules for the Constitution. He wanted a small federal government with only the powers listed in the Constitution. He knew a big government could be bad, but he thought a simple reading of the Constitution could also become bad. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true rulebook for the United States because it said the country was made of many states.

Many people stopped using the commuter log in the third month of the project. This was a problem. We do not know why. The weather in New England is cold in the third month, so many people do not commute by bicycle or on foot. Also, students and teachers are busy finishing schoolwork. They may not think about the log. Plus, December is vacation time. People do not need to come to school. The project started with a lot of energy. This might cause the log to decrease. We created a Carpool Challenge Week in March to make the project more exciting. This helped the log submissions go up. We tried to make people use the log by giving prizes. We gave out gift cards to local stores. We also thought about giving bigger prizes like bicycles or cars. This might have helped. We did not change the prizes during the project. If we had given bigger prizes later, more people might have used the log.

An ETF is a security that follows an index, a commodity, or a group of assets like an index fund. It trades like a stock. An ETF has the benefits of an index fund and single stock ownership. It can be sold short, bought on margin, and bought in small amounts. ETFs have low expense ratios, but you pay a commission for trades. There are many types of ETFs. It is good to check if stated benefits, like diversification, really exist. We will examine the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings to see if owning the ETF is better than owning the stocks. The top 10 holdings make up 63.58% of the ETF. Here are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

The chart shows that the return of a portfolio of the top 10 stocks is 6.11% higher than the ETF. The Beta of the top 10 stocks is 0.12 lower. This means the top 10 stocks could have a higher return with a lower risk. But we need to check if the difference is real or just chance. To do that, we need to see the standard deviations of the top 10 stocks and the ETF.

Edgar Allan Poe wrote a good poem called “Dream-Land.” In this poem, Poe uses the word “Thulé.” This word comes from Virgil's writing. Virgil used it for an island north of Britain. Some people think Poe got the idea from a poem by Goethe. In Goethe's poem, a king loses his wife and drinks too much. He then dies. Poe's poem about Thulé is like Goethe's. Both poems have a king who is sad and alone. Poe's poem describes a dark, lonely place with dead friends. This is like the king in Goethe's poem. Poe's poem also has a king who gives up everything but a goblet. This is like how the king in Goethe's poem dies. Poe used the word Thulé in two poems. He used it in “The Pit and the Pendulum” and “Dream-Land.” These poems are like each other. Poe liked Goethe. He admired Tennyson. Poe would have known Goethe's work because of this.

In California law, a customer hurt by a slip and fall in a store might win extra money if the store's manager was really bad. The manager must have acted with wrong purpose, or have done a thing that was very bad and did not care about people's safety. The customer must show the manager was warned about the problem twice and did not clean it up fast. This could make the manager's actions seem bad. The court might find the manager's actions were bad because many people slipped and fell before. The manager did not clean up the spill quickly, even after two warnings. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, a worker told the manager there was applesauce on the floor. The manager said he was too busy. Another worker told him at 5:15 PM, and he said the same thing. At 5:30 PM, the customer slipped and fell. Before this, five people had slipped and fallen in 2009. The customer is now asking for money because of her injury. The law in California lets someone win extra money if a store's manager acts with "oppression, fraud, or malice." The manager must have wanted to cause harm, or done a really bad thing with no care for people's safety. If the manager knew the spill was dangerous and did not clean it up, his actions could be seen as bad. A court might find the manager's actions were bad because many people had slipped and fallen.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. We talked much about if Islam is a bad religion. Now, this question is even more important. Since 9/11, news about Islam changed. We saw a president, Barack Obama, with a Muslim background. A long time ago, we could not have seen this. The story of Muhammad is like a book. It is interesting, but it does not show the true Muhammad. I thought Muhammad forced people to become Muslim. But the book shows Muhammad as a good man who was misunderstood. People liked his teaching. He did not need to prove his power. He just lived in truth and did miracles. This is like stealing from Jesus. The stories in the book are like proof of conversion to Islam. But many are third-person accounts. This makes them seem less true. The book also tries to show Muhammad as a good man. But history says he was not. If Muslims know this, they will think differently.

Jesus' ideas and beliefs were changed after his time. Christianity moved away from its start. Today, people understand more about Christianity and progress is happening. Some people still follow old ways, but they are not big enough to change everything. In the future, more Christians will study Jesus' original teachings. They want to find out what he really said and did. This will take time, but it will happen. Christianity will change back to how it was before. More people will believe and practice the same way. In the past, Christians were hated by the Romans. Later, the Romans became Christian. Our country changed from slavery to leadership. Christianity will change too. People will read Jesus' words like stories, not as facts. What happened after Jesus? Long ago, there was only Judaism. It was about one god, holy books, and the Hebrew people. They divided into groups. The Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E.

I think The Jungle shows that people are naturally selfish and only care about themselves. They want good things for themselves and don't care about others. The book shows this in many ways. One way is the factory owners and managers. They want big, successful companies and factories. They don't care about anyone or anything that gets hurt. They don't care about the smoke from the factories or the animal waste around Packingtown. They don't care about their workers either. They make workers work long hours and can lay them off without warning or help. There weren't many laws to protect workers during that time. Managers and owners could do what they wanted. Workers had no organizations to help them. Unions sometimes hurt workers. Workers were very badly treated and couldn't leave, so they were like slaves.

Many authors use different ways to make readers feel or think about important things. Scott Fitzgerald uses these ways in his book, The Great Gatsby. He often pairs words that don't usually go together. He also gives meaning to symbols and uses them. In his book, he builds meanings for colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. He uses the meanings of these colors to make readers feel about important things.

Scott Fitzgerald makes white/gray stand for uniformity. White is nicer and higher class. Gray is older and faded. In the beginning of the book, many people wear white. Daisy and Jordan are always in white. Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party. Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle. Catherine is powdered milky white. The only time people are not wearing white is when Nick sees Gatsby's party. The halls are gaudy with primary colors. Nick goes down the white chasms of lower New York. The names of people at Gatsby's party are gray. Catherine's apartment is one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses. Plain people and places are white or gray. Daisy and Jordan had a white girlhood. There are gray cars and gray land in the valley of ashes. The Italian child is gray. The dog-seller is a gray old man.

Scott Fitzgerald uses these colors to show unimportance or uniformity. He first uses this with Daisy. After a long time without using either color, he describes Daisy as dressed in white in a little white roadster. Readers start to see Daisy as less of a character, more like something that Gatsby wants. He uses this technique more with Daisy. There is a gray haze of Daisy's fur collar. She is again in a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is a good place for farming, with a warm, sunny climate. Farmers grow many types of crops, like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. People in the area want organic food from local farms. Some farms offer tours and other activities, like hiking and birdwatching. This can help farmers make money and improve the environment.

Organic farming has some advantages. It has more plants and animals because it uses no chemicals. But it also costs more. Farmers need to do more work to keep pests away and fertilize the soil. Also, organic farms do not have the same efficiency as large farms. Some other activities to help wildlife cost more, like planting cover crops, removing invasive plants, and managing plant growth.

The land in this story is near the town of Potrero, in San Diego County. It is 160 acres with chaparral, nonnative grassland, and oak woodland. It is near a national forest. Many animals and plants live here, some of which are endangered. Native Americans lived here for a long time. In the 1800s, people used it for grazing and selling wood.

I looked at a piece of land from a real estate website and found government programs to help small farmers. I also found an organic farm in the same area as a model.

Culture is important in negotiations. It is not easy to define culture. Culture is not the same everywhere. It is not just about one country or place. Culture is not simple, and it is not easy to understand. Some people think they know about a culture, but this can be wrong. For example, people might say "All Russians are stubborn" or "All Japanese are friendly." These ideas are too simple and not true for all people in these cultures.

To understand a culture, a negotiator must think about what the culture means. The negotiator must understand how the culture will affect the talks. Comparing cultures can be helpful. A negotiator might study a culture's history or understand its beliefs.

When a negotiator goes to a foreign place for a negotiation, he or she should respect the culture and traditions. This can help with communication and make the negotiation easier. Company culture is also important. A corporate culture can be different from place to place. Corporate culture can affect how employees work and communicate.

Values are very important to understand. They explain why people in a culture do things. If a culture values respect, a negotiator will not shame others in a negotiation. If a culture values a hard bargain, a negotiator will not give in easily. A negotiator should learn about his or her opponent's personal values to make the negotiation better.

The statement "There is no God" is said by a foolish person. This quote is in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible. It is also believed by Thomas Aquinas. Both authors defend the idea of God, but we must start with the idea that they are correct. To compare their arguments, we must assume they are both right about God. Their arguments are for the same God, so we cannot use another idea of God. Neither argument gives a complete reason to believe in God.

St. Anselm's argument is about finding God's existence in our own mind. He says we do not need evidence outside ourselves to know God exists. This is called faith. Aquinas says God's existence can be proven with reason and evidence. This is helpful for spreading Christianity because it does not need people to accept something that cannot be proven. Aquinas has five arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument shows that God's existence is logical and necessary.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince named Buddha was born. He became enlightened and started Buddhism. The most common form is Theravada Buddhism, which is around twenty-five hundred years old. Today, Buddhism looks different than when Buddha was alive.

In Sri Lanka, there is a water-cutting ceremony. Monks and people from the Buddhist community take part. Buddha did not teach about this ceremony. This shows how Theravada Buddhism has changed over time.

Theravada Buddhism has changed both inside and outside the Buddhist community. Internal forces are changes made by members of the Buddhist community. External forces are changes made by non-Buddhists. Hostile forces want to harm Buddhism, while benign forces do not.

We need to learn about the basic beliefs of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge. The Triple Gem is the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the Tripitaka, which has three parts. The Sutta Pitaka has Buddhist teachings. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has Buddhist ideas.

To end the cycle of death and rebirth, called Sansara, one must understand Anatta, no soul, Dukkha, inherent suffering, and Anicca, impermanence. Monks and laymen have rules to follow. Laymen have five rules. Monks have more rules. The four noble truths are: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, and suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico were rivals for a long time, from 1836 to 1893. The big fight was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. The United States won and got new land. Other problems happened, too, until before World War I.  The rivalry began because Americans and Mexicans had different beliefs about religion, culture, and land.  Other countries with borders often have these kinds of problems. Mexico and Cuba are like this with the United States.  They have long problems with the United States. Other Latin American countries have good relations with the United States.  Religion caused problems between the United States and Mexico, like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. The United States and Mexico did not trust each other because of their past with England and Spain.  Diehl and Goerts list 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most were about land and border problems.  Bandits and outlaws caused big problems.  The rivalry ended when Mexico became dependent on the United States and the United States changed to focus on economics.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly and unexpectedly sick. Before, I worked as a nurse. I chose this job because it gave me safety and security. I heard, "People always get sick. You can always find work." So, even if I dreamed of being a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing.

But now, I am 46 years old, single, and not able to work. I have no money left. I live on Social Security Disability. Every day is hard. Nothing is certain anymore. But, I could not live this long without my family and friends helping me.

There will always be emergencies in life. Some things are too big to overcome alone. We need to stop relying on big government. Instead, we should learn to trust each other and ask for help.

The Conservatives in the U.S. talk about rugged individualism. But our early ancestors didn't succeed alone. They helped each other and shared resources.

So, prepare for emergencies. I have a disaster kit and supplies. But, also, get to know your neighbors. This way, we can help each other.

Why do animals change over time? Are there rules that guide these changes? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that even now, it's hard to describe animal shapes in math. But now, math is used to study animal growth and history. Our study looks at how math can explain how animals change. We use X-ray images of a type of snail, Prunum, to find numbers that can help us make math models. These models show possible shape changes. We combine this with experiments and descriptions to learn about big changes in this group of snails.

A snail's shell is like a long tube that goes in a spiral. This spiral has sections called whorls. There is a line where each whorl ends. Most shells have the biggest whorl at the top. The animal lives in the spiral part called the spire. The front end is the apex, and the back end is the base. The opening that the animal lives in is called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different sides. The usual side shows the aperture facing forward, with the apex pointing up. To count whorls, look at the shell from the top and find the first line between the whorls. Count the whorls from this line. Each whorl can be thought of as a path the aperture takes through time and space as the snail grows.

This path can be shown with math. Once we have a math formula, we can change the numbers to see how the snail's shell changes.

In Indonesia, babies and infants have not gotten healthier much in the last ten years. While the country is close to meeting some Millennium Development Goals, like clean water and toilets, others, like child and mother health, are not improving fast enough. There are many reasons for this, and the health system needs to be stronger instead of focusing on specific programs.

Indonesia has 72% of births with skilled workers, but many are midwives who cannot help with complicated pregnancies. There are also fewer cases of diarrhea in children under five treated by a health professional. Postnatal care is also a problem. Cesarian-section rates are low, and there is more access to healthcare in cities than in rural areas. The poorest and richest use healthcare services differently.

The next step is to decide how to improve neonatal and maternal care. Should Indonesia focus on specific programs or strengthen the whole health system? Programs can solve problems quickly and have clear goals, but they can also cause problems, like not enough money for other areas and uncoordinated services. It is important to consider these drawbacks.

Victorian novels usually focus on detail and the aristocracy. Two books, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have mystery and unusual things. This makes the characters stronger and shows their feelings.

In Oliver Twist, strange things happen in dreams. They show Oliver's thoughts and feelings. When he remembers the shooting, he sees and hears things again. He feels pain, but it is not like before. He cannot control the shooting. He is in danger, but he does not try to help himself. He feels like he has no power over his life. He might be broken by Fagin. He could not do anything to save himself.

The day goes quickly in Wuthering Heights. There is no day, only night. Night is long and quiet, but short. There are no good times.

I helped students in an after school program. I was good at English and reading. I helped a boy named Adrian who had trouble reading. I thought he spoke perfect English, but he was having strange problems. He knew some letters, but not others. His mother spoke only Spanish. She said Adrian could read, but not English. I helped him learn the English alphabet and letters. This could help other children who speak English but have trouble reading. The problem is getting worse. We need many solutions. Different ways to help children learn. We need dual language programs. We need teachers who speak other languages. We need help for children who speak little English. We need all these things to help all children.

From when we are children, we learn about something bigger than us. Some go to school to learn about it, others go to temple, or look inside themselves. Many accept the religions given to them by their parents, but some reject them. We all search for a light in the dark. We choose different paths to find our true selves.

“A cardinal,” my father said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on our porch, listening to the rain. He had lost weight. His hair was thinner. He stared out at the rain, not looking at me. I felt alone and afraid. I hugged him, sat closer, and looked at the rain with him.

My father died in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. He suffered from chemo and radiation. He did not want me to see him die. I did not go. I waited in bed for three days. No one called me.

The Gothic Novel is old and new, a mix of old and modern. It is praised and blamed. It has no real depth, but it is very scary. The first Gothic Novel, The Castle of Otranto, uses old and new ideas. It mixes old theatre and new nature. It is a new way to write. The Gothic Novel lasts long because it combines old and new. It is old and new to people far in time from the first Gothic Novel.

One big idea in Gothic Novels is Chivalry. Chivalry is the training of a knight. It is important in Gothic Novels because it shows a good knight. The Gothic Novel uses Chivalry to make the past seem better. The writer, Walpole, wrote The Castle of Otranto during a political time. He was unhappy with the future. He thought the goodness of people in the past was lost. He shows this in his novel, especially with the character Frederic. Frederic is a prince. He has suffered. He is brave and kind. He is a good example of a knight. Walpole uses this to show his view of the present.

Supply chain management is a system of moving goods from customer order to delivery. It was started in 1982 by Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver explained that supply chain management helps people plan, do, and control work to meet customer needs quickly and well. There are six important parts to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Production is the first step in the supply chain. It is the start of the whole process. The production stage plans when, why, where, and how to make products. Managers need to know what customers want. They can find out by looking at the market. The market shows what customers need. After knowing what customers want, managers can decide what products to make and how many to make. Then, they decide where to make the products. They choose a place with good volume and quality. They also check if customers will be satisfied. After deciding the location, managers focus on work schedules and equipment care. Production is very important. Every detail must be planned well. If not, it can cost the company time and money. For example, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. Both stores have a plan for every job. They have a uniform layout and a process for receiving shipments. This helps the company work without confusion.

The next important part is supply. Supply is about making good choices to decide what a facility can do and who to work with. A company may have many parts for making a product. Each part needs different equipment and workers. The manager must choose the best part for each job. They may also choose to work with other companies. This is to get products made quickly while keeping costs low.

Hitler is alive in Burma, a sign says.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner. She holds a cardboard sign. It says, "Hitler is alive in Burma" with a Sharpie. Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. A group of soldiers rules it. In 1962, they took power with a coup. In 2007, many people protested. They used bright robes. Many people joined. At first, the soldiers let the protests happen. But then, they started fighting. They attacked monasteries. They killed a Japanese photographer named Kenji Nagai. The soldiers said many people died. A soldier who left the army said, "Many people died, more than the government said."

This is not new. Many governments want complete power. Early Roman leaders said they were gods. They ruled over all things. Japanese leaders say they are gods. Our current president talks to a man named Ted Haggard. He leads a group called Stupid People Worldwide.

Other examples are:
- The protests at Tiananmen Square in 1989. Many people died.
- The Rwandan genocide in the 1990s. Many people were killed.
- Hitler's Third Reich. Many people were killed because of their religion.

Duke Ellington's music is important in jazz. He played piano and led his band for a long time. He could make his music sound good with many different players. He wrote music that let soloists play freely and made the whole band sound good. He used many different sounds and made his music sound new and interesting. The Grove Music dictionary says he used his voice like an instrument in his music. In 'Creole Love Call,' he used his voice in a blues song with six parts. He also made good use of his band members' sounds. In 'Hot and Bothered,' he made a good sound with a quiet trumpet and scat singing. 'It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)' used a trombone player's sound well.

She wanted something, but she did not know what. She felt this way since she was 14. Now, at 17, she still felt this way. She liked people, not things. Boys did not interest her. Some tried to talk to her, but none made her happy. She did not know why. After thinking for years, she still did not know. So, she lived her life, always asking herself about her feelings.

A day at home was usually calm. Her parents were kind and calm. They did not argue. They argued only when she wanted to be free and independent. She was a lively girl with a nice personality.

Today was different. As she walked from room to room, she heard a scream. She ran to the kitchen and saw her mother on the ground. She was in pain and said, "Take me to the hospital." Her daughter helped her mother to the car and drove to the hospital.

At the hospital, she felt fear, but she was busy helping her mother. She carried her mother to a bed and called for help. The doctors took her mother away.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to grab a vase.

This study shows that eating the Mediterranean Diet, with high “alternate Mediterranean” (aMed) score, lowers risk of heart disease and stroke. The aMed diet has more plant foods and less animal products. Some previous studies showed this diet helps weight loss and lowers cholesterol. This study followed 74,886 women. They reported food intake six times. More than 95% stayed in the study for 20 years. The study found 2,391 heart disease cases, 1,763 stroke cases, and 1,077 cardiovascular deaths. Women who ate the Mediterranean Diet the most had lower risk of both heart disease and stroke (relative risk, 0.71).

In 2007, the United States had a big financial trouble. Many people lost jobs. The housing market was bad. Big companies were in trouble. This bad time started in 1999. The Clinton government made rules easier. This helped start the problem. Steven Holmes from the New York Times said this would cause trouble. Many bad things made the economy bad. The way mortgages were used caused problems. Homes and banks got into trouble. In 2007, the top banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts. This was one-third of the USA's GDP. Many banks were in big trouble. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also had big debts. The government took control of them in 2008.

Exposition is not good.

You know "Show, don't tell," but you still write too much. Not good. In film, exposition is when one character tells another much information. In writing, you do the telling.

Example: You read about a heroine who met her husband. You read about their marriage and his death. But you don't read much about them. You want to know more about him. You want to know how he made her happy. You want to know why she loved him. You want to feel her pain when he died. So, you want the author to write more.

Sometimes, you want to write quickly. You want to introduce a new character. You know many things about him. He was in the Air Force. He now manages a gas station. He was married twice. No children. Likes fishing. Dreams of owning the gas station. Ate Eggs Benedict for breakfast. But you don't write all this. You write less.

Write more about characters. Write less about what happened. Write so readers feel connected.

I watched two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. The first was live on NBC 4. It showed a man named Shad Hostettler. He stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. The news said he was arrested. They showed his picture. The second story was about a young man, Travis Buyers, who was shot in Sharon Woods. He was injured and the police were investigating. I thought they did not spend enough time on this story. They did not say much about it. The next story was about a hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. A .22 caliber bullet from a rifle hit it. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for tips. The next story was about rain and thunderstorms. The temperatures would be high on the weekend. The next story was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. The news said he was about six feet tall and weighed about 150 pounds. I thought they talked too much about his race. Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a convicted drug kingpin. He was from Texas. He was sent to prison for 300 months. The news said he was Hispanic. I thought that was not important to the story.

There is a strong connection between brothers. This link is special and cannot be changed. In this bond, many feelings exist. These feelings include love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers know each other well. They understand each other more than anyone else with this bond. When looking at their brother, they see themselves. In difficult times, the true nature of this bond shows. This bond has a price. To understand these feelings, one must deal with their consequences. When a brother looks in another brother’s eyes, they see their true self. Their actions and the results of those actions show their true nature. In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers explore this theme. They go on a journey in a beautiful place. They feel many strong emotions. One brother dies. The theme is shown through the main character, Doodle, and his brother. The narrator’s view also shows the feelings of Doodle and his view of the world. These feelings affect his actions.

The main character’s actions are mainly driven by one feeling: pride. From their first adventure, to their last, the main character feels angry towards Doodle. He wanted a brother to teach his skills like holding his breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp. He also wanted a brother to race to Horsehead Landing and perch with him in the great pine behind the barn. It is impossible for Doodle, who has a weak heart, to do these things. The main character’s dreams are crushed. He even thinks of killing Doodle. But his heart melts when Doodle smiles at him. This shows that his wish to kill Doodle was not strong. He loves his brother.

The human brain is a complex system for thinking and learning. Starting with simple tools, people began comparing it to a wax tablet, then a sheet of paper, then a book, and finally a computer. As you study the brain, remember that these comparisons are not perfect.

Information starts when the senses take in light, sound, touch, or smell. The brain changes these signals into electrical messages. The brain works in two ways. One way is to put together simple parts. For example, when you see a black box, you first notice the color and shape. The brain then decides it is a box. The other way is to use decisions made earlier to make recognition easier. For example, the brain might guess it is a black box, not a hole.

Attention decides what information is important. For example, you might notice your name in a noisy room, but not the grass under your shoes. There are many stages of processing. The results of processing are changed by attention.

To think, the brain needs to store information. There are different kinds of memory. For example, there is short-term memory for a few seconds and long-term memory for years. Information is stored in different ways. For example, words can be stored by how they look, sound, or mean. The brain keeps information by looping electrical signals through certain neurons.

How the brain organizes knowledge is not clear. Some models say there are links between ideas, like a map. Others say it is like a computer program or how the brain works physically.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the future threat of technology and capitalism. He shows this in the novel Brave New World. In this world, people value community more than themselves. They are taught from birth to want happiness. The people are like puppets, controlled by the World Controller. The author's complaints about capitalism are like those in Marxism. He uses words like "homogeny" and "reification" to show the problems with the economy.

Capitalism is shown as "false consciousness". This means that people do not know their real relationship to other classes. They are not aware of their place in the system. The common people in Brave New World are taught to want to spend and consume. They do not know they are being controlled. They believe the World Controller's lies.

The novel shows that capitalism controls people. The lower classes, like Delta and Gamma, do not know they are being manipulated. The upper classes, Alphas and Betas, know but do not do anything. The relationships between people are not real. They are shallow. People do not show deep emotions. The story shows that people are happy to stay in their place in the hierarchy. They do not want to change.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Many students, including me, find it difficult to get around campus. My first year, I lived in East Halls, far from the center. It took up to 25 minutes to walk to classes in Willard building. This was worse when the weather was bad. Recently, this area has changed. New buildings and sports fields fill the space. As the campus grows, it becomes harder to move around.

A friend told me that the best way to move around is by bicycle. Bikes are good for your body and the environment. However, the campus is not always friendly to bicycles. Some roads are difficult to ride on. Pollock Road, the best route to Thomas building, is straight but tough. I live off campus and can’t walk to class every day. My bike saves me time. Without it, I would spend over two and a half hours walking each week. I would have less time for other activities.
